<MemberLayout title="Information Security Policy">
  <div class="policy-page">
    <div class="policy-header">
      <a href="/members/documents" class="back-link">&larr; Back to Documents</a>
      <h1>Information Security Policy</h1>
      <p class="policy-meta">Alnmouth Village Golf Club &middot; 27 October 2023</p>
    </div>
    <div class="policy-content">
      <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
      <p>This Policy Document encompasses all aspects of security surrounding confidential company information and must be distributed to all company employees. All company employees must read this document in its entirety and sign the form confirming they have read and understand this policy fully. This document will be reviewed and updated by Management on an annual basis or when relevant to include newly developed security standards into the policy.</p>

      <h2>2. Information Security Policy</h2>
      <p>Alnmouth Village Golf Club handles sensitive cardholder information daily. Sensitive Information must have adequate safeguards in place to protect them, to protect cardholder privacy, to ensure compliance with various regulations and to guard the future of the organization.</p>
      <p>Alnmouth Village Golf Club commits to respecting the privacy of all its customers and to protecting any data about customers from outside parties. To this end management are committed to maintaining a secure environment in which to process cardholder information so that we can meet these promises.</p>
      <p>Employees handling sensitive cardholder data should ensure:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Handle Company and cardholder information in a manner that fits with their sensitivity</li>
        <li>Limit personal use of company information and telecommunication systems</li>
        <li>Do not use e-mail, internet and other Company resources to engage in any action that is offensive, threatening, discriminatory, defamatory, or illegal</li>
        <li>Do not disclose personnel information unless authorized</li>
        <li>Protect sensitive cardholder information</li>
        <li>Keep passwords and accounts secure</li>
        <li>Request approval from management prior to establishing any new software or hardware, third party connections, etc.</li>
        <li>Do not install unauthorized software or hardware unless you have explicit management approval</li>
        <li>Always leave desks clear of sensitive cardholder data and lock computer screens when unattended</li>
        <li>Information security incidents must be reported without delay to the individual responsible for incident response</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>3. Acceptable Use Policy</h2>
      <p>Management is committed to protecting the employees, partners and the Company from illegal or damaging actions by individuals, either knowingly or unknowingly.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Employees are responsible for exercising good judgment regarding the reasonableness of personal use</li>
        <li>Employees should ensure that they have appropriate credentials and are authenticated for the use of technologies</li>
        <li>Employees should take all necessary steps to prevent unauthorized access to confidential data including cardholder data</li>
        <li>Keep passwords secure and do not share accounts</li>
        <li>All PCs, laptops and workstations should be secured with a password-protected screensaver</li>
        <li>All POS and PIN entry devices should be appropriately protected and secured</li>
        <li>Employees must use extreme caution when opening e-mail attachments received from unknown senders</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>4. Disciplinary Action</h2>
      <p>Violation of the standards, policies and procedures presented in this document by an employee will result in disciplinary action, from warnings or reprimands up to and including termination of employment.</p>

      <h2>5. Protect Stored Data</h2>
      <p>All sensitive cardholder data stored and handled by Alnmouth Village Golf Club and its employees must be securely protected against unauthorized use at all times. Any sensitive card data that is no longer required for business reasons must be discarded in a secure and irrecoverable manner.</p>
      <p>It is strictly prohibited to store:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The contents of the payment card magnetic stripe (track data) on any media whatsoever</li>
        <li>The CVV/CVC (the 3 or 4 digit number on the signature panel on the reverse of the payment card) on any media whatsoever</li>
        <li>The PIN or the encrypted PIN Block under any circumstance</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>6. Information Classification</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Confidential data</strong> &ndash; includes cardholder data and information assets for which there are legal requirements for preventing disclosure</li>
        <li><strong>Internal Use data</strong> &ndash; information that the data owner feels should be protected to prevent unauthorized disclosure</li>
        <li><strong>Public data</strong> &ndash; information that may be freely disseminated</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>7. Access to Sensitive Cardholder Data</h2>
      <p>All access to sensitive cardholder data should be controlled and authorized. Access rights should be restricted to least privileges necessary to perform job responsibilities. Access is restricted to employees that have a legitimate need to view such information.</p>

      <h2>8. Physical Security</h2>
      <p>Access to sensitive information in both hard and soft media format must be physically restricted to prevent unauthorized individuals from obtaining sensitive data.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A list of devices that accept payment card data should be maintained including make, model, location and serial number</li>
        <li>POS devices surfaces should be periodically inspected to detect tampering or substitution</li>
        <li>Personnel should verify the identity of any third party personnel claiming to repair or maintain devices</li>
        <li>Media containing sensitive cardholder information must be handled and distributed in a secure manner</li>
        <li>Visitors must always be escorted by a trusted employee when in areas that hold sensitive cardholder information</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>9. Protect Data in Transit</h2>
      <p>All sensitive cardholder data must be protected securely if it is to be transported physically or electronically. Card holder data must never be sent over the internet via email, instant chat or any other end user technologies without strong encryption.</p>

      <h2>10. Disposal of Stored Data</h2>
      <p>All data must be securely disposed of when no longer required, regardless of the media or application type on which it is stored. All hard copies of cardholder data must be manually destroyed when no longer required. Alnmouth Village Golf Club will have procedures for the destruction of hardcopy materials requiring crosscut shredding, incineration or pulping.</p>

      <h2>11. Security Awareness and Procedures</h2>
      <p>The policies and procedures outlined must be incorporated into company practice to maintain a high level of security awareness. The protection of sensitive data demands regular training of all employees and contractors.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>All employees that handle sensitive information will undergo background checks before commencing employment</li>
        <li>All third parties with access to credit card account numbers are contractually obligated to comply with PCI/DSS</li>
        <li>Company security policies must be reviewed annually and updated as needed</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>12. Network Security</h2>
      <p>Firewalls must be implemented at each internet connection and between any demilitarized zone and the internal company network. A network diagram detailing all connections must be maintained and reviewed every 6 months.</p>

      <h2>13. System and Password Policy</h2>
      <p>All users with access to card holder data must have a unique ID. All user ID's for terminated users must be deactivated or removed immediately. User accounts will be locked after more than 5 unsuccessful attempts for a minimum of 30 minutes.</p>
      <p>A strong password must:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Be as long as possible (never shorter than 6 characters)</li>
        <li>Include mixed-case letters, if possible</li>
        <li>Include digits and punctuation marks, if possible</li>
        <li>Not be based on any personal information</li>
        <li>Not be based on any dictionary word, in any language</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>14. Anti-virus Policy</h2>
      <p>All machines must be configured to run the latest anti-virus software with automatic daily updates and periodic scanning enabled. The antivirus software must be capable of detecting all known types of malicious software.</p>

      <h2>15. Patch Management Policy</h2>
      <p>All workstations, servers, software and system components must have up-to-date system security patches installed. Security patches must be installed within one month of release from the respective vendor.</p>

      <h2>16. Remote Access Policy</h2>
      <p>Secure remote access must be strictly controlled via two factor authentication. Vendor accounts will only be enabled during the time period access is required. Remote access connections will be disconnected automatically after 30 minutes of inactivity.</p>

      <h2>17. Vulnerability Management Policy</h2>
      <p>Alnmouth Village Golf Club will run internal and external network vulnerability scans at least quarterly and after any significant change in the network. Quarterly external scans must be performed by an Approved Scanning Vendor (ASV) qualified by PCI SSC.</p>

      <h2>18. Configuration Standards</h2>
      <p>Information systems that process, transmit, or store card holder data must be configured in accordance with the applicable standard for that class of device or system. All network device configurations must be checked annually against the configuration boilerplate.</p>

      <h2>19. Change Control Process</h2>
      <p>Changes to information resources shall be managed and executed according to a formal change control process. All change requests shall be logged whether approved or rejected. A risk assessment shall be performed for all changes. Changes shall be tested in an isolated, controlled environment prior to implementation.</p>

      <h2>20. Audit and Log Review</h2>
      <p>Audit logs must be maintained for a minimum of 3 months online (available for immediate analysis) and 12 months offline. Logs cover operating system events, database audit logs, firewalls &amp; network switch logs, IDS logs, antivirus logs, CCTV recordings, and file integrity monitoring.</p>

      <h2>21. Secure Application Development</h2>
      <p>The Secure Application Development policy guides developers' decisions during the software development lifecycle (SDLC). Each phase maps to security activities including design reviews, threat modelling, coding best practices, static analysis, vulnerability assessment, and configuration review.</p>

      <h2>22. Penetration Testing Methodology</h2>
      <p>Technical tests must follow the OSSTMM methodology at network, system and application level. Tests must identify vulnerabilities documented by OWASP and SANS, as well as those in PCI DSS standard.</p>

      <h2>23. Incident Response Plan</h2>
      <p>The Incident Response Plan is to be tested once annually. In the event of a suspected security breach, the security officer will carry out an initial investigation and alert management and all relevant parties. The PCI Response Team will investigate and assist in limiting exposure and mitigating risks.</p>

      <h2>24. Roles and Responsibilities</h2>
      <p>The Chief Security Officer is responsible for overseeing all aspects of information security, including creating and distributing security policies and maintaining a formal security awareness program for all employees.</p>

      <h2>25. Third Party Access to Cardholder Data</h2>
      <p>All third-party companies providing critical services must provide an agreed Service Level Agreement and comply with PCI DSS security requirements. They must acknowledge their responsibility for securing cardholder data.</p>

      <h2>26. User Access Management</h2>
      <p>Access is controlled through a formal user registration process. Each user is identified by a unique user ID. Access for remote users shall be subject to authorization and provided in accordance with the Remote Access Policy.</p>

      <h2>27. Access Control Policy</h2>
      <p>Access control systems protect the interests of all users. Access rights will be accorded following the principles of least privilege and need to know. A formal process shall be conducted at regular intervals to review users' access rights.</p>

      <h2>28. Wireless Policy</h2>
      <p>Installation or use of any wireless device intended to connect to company networks is prohibited without approval. A quarterly test should be run to discover any unauthorized wireless access points. If wireless technology is approved, it must implement industry best practices (IEEE 802.11i) and strong encryption.</p>
